{"title_page": "Tsutomu Yamaguchi", "text_new": "{{short description|Japanese atomic bombing survivor}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name       = Tsutomu Yamaguchi\n|native_name= \u5c71\u53e3 \u5f4a\n|native_name_lang=ja\n|image      = Tsutomu-Yamaguchi-Japanes-001.jpg\n|caption    = Tsutomu Yamaguchi in 2009\n|birth_date = {{Birth date|1916|3|16|mf=y}}\n|birth_place= [[Nagasaki]], [[Empire of Japan|Japan]]\n|death_date = {{Death date and age|2010|1|4|1916|3|16|mf=y}}\n|death_place= [[Nagasaki]], [[Japan]]\n|occupation = [[Engineer]]\n|spouse     =\n|children   = 3 Hio oehdnd a beter ;ife for dwhat je kid iwb suwed disdun wud hw[\n}}\n{{Nihongo|'''Tsutomu Yamaguchi'''|\u5c71\u53e3 \u5f4a|Yamaguchi Tsutomu|}} (March 16, 1916{{spaced ndash}}January 4, 2010) was a survivor of both the [[Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki|Hiroshima and Nagasaki atomic bombings]] during [[World War II]]. Although at least 70 people are known to have been affected by both bombings,<ref>{{cite news|script-title=ja:\u5e83\u5cf6\u30fb\u9577\u5d0e\u3067\uff12\u5ea6\u88ab\u7206\u3001\u7d04\uff11\uff16\uff10\u4eba\u3000\u5e83\u5cf6\u7948\u5ff5\u9928\u304c\u8abf\u67fb|newspaper=[[Asahi Shimbun]]|date=2005-08-01|language= Japanese|trans-title=160 Double A-bomb Survivors Found, [[Hiroshima National Peace Memorial Hall for the Atomic Bomb Victims]] says.|quote= \u5e83\u5cf6\u3001\u9577\u5d0e\u3078\u306e\u539f\u7206\u6295\u4e0b\u5f8c\u3001\u4e21\u5e02\u3067\uff12\u5ea6\u88ab\u7206\u3057\u305f\u53ef\u80fd\u6027\u306e\u3042\u308b\u4eba\u304c\u5c11\u306a\u304f\u3068\u3082\u7d04\uff11\uff16\uff10\u4eba\u306b\u306e\u307c\u308b\u3053\u3068\u304c\u3001\u56fd\u7acb\u5e83\u5cf6\u539f\u7206\u6b7b\u6ca1\u8005\u8ffd\u60bc\u5e73\u548c\u7948\u5ff5\u9928\uff08\u5e83\u5cf6\u5e02\uff09\u306e\u8abf\u67fb\u3067\u660e\u3089\u304b\u306b\u306a\u3063\u305f\u3002}}</ref> he is the only person to have been officially recognized by the [[government of Japan]] as surviving both explosions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Double atomic bomb survivor dies in Japan|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/34722073|agency=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[NBC News]]|location=Tokyo|date=2010-01-06|accessdate=2011-01-25|quote=Tsutomu Yamaguchi, the only person officially recognized as a survivor of both the Hiroshima and Nagasaki atomic bombings at the end of World War II, has died at age 93.}}</ref>\n\nYamaguchi, a resident of [[Nagasaki]], was in [[Hiroshima]] on business for his employer [[Mitsubishi Heavy Industries]] when the city was bombed at 8:15&nbsp;am, on August 6, 1945. He returned to Nagasaki the following day and, despite his wounds, he returned to work on August 9, the day of the second atomic bombing. That morning, whilst being berated by his supervisor as \"crazy\" after describing how one bomb had destroyed the city, the Nagasaki bomb detonated.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9_VsNZl6LGU&t=1m6s Survivor's story (ABC News, Australia, uploaded 2010Jan6)]</ref> In 1957, he was recognized as a [[hibakusha]] (''explosion-affected person'') of the Nagasaki bombing, but it was not until March 24, 2009, that the government of Japan officially recognized his presence in Hiroshima three days earlier. He died of [[stomach cancer]] on January 4, 2010, at the age of 93.\n\n==Early life==\nYamaguchi was born on March 16, 1916. He joined [[Mitsubishi Heavy Industries]] in the 1930s and worked as a draftsman designing oil tankers.<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news|author=|title=Tsutomu Yamaguchi|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/6943088/Tsutomu-Yamaguchi.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=2010-01-06|accessdate=2010-01-07}}</ref>\n\n==Second World War==\nYamaguchi \"never thought Japan should start a war\". He continued his work with Mitsubishi Heavy Industries, but soon Japanese industry began to suffer heavily as resources became scarce and tankers were sunk.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> As the war ground on, he was so despondent over the state of the country that he considered [[Seppuku#In_modern_times|killing his]] [[familicide|family]] with an overdose of [[sleeping pills]] in the event that Japan lost.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/>\n\n===Hiroshima bombing===\nYamaguchi lived and worked in Nagasaki, but in the summer of 1945 he was in Hiroshima for a three-month-long business trip.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> On August 6 he was preparing to leave the city with two colleagues, Akira Iwanaga and Kuniyoshi Sato, and was on his way to the station when he realised he had forgotten his [[Hanko (stamp)|hanko]] (a type of travel stamp common in Japan) and returned to his workplace to get it.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news|first=Justin|last=McCurry|title=A little deaf in one ear \u2013 meet the Japanese man who survived Hiroshima and Nagasaki|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/mar/25/hiroshima-nagasaki-survivor-japan|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=2009-03-25|accessdate=2010-01-11|location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"Times\">{{cite web|url=https://blogs.thetimes.co.uk/section/asia-exile/20579/the-luckiest-or-unluckiest-man-in-the-world-tsutomu-yamaguchi-double-a-bomb-victim/ |title=The luckiest or unluckiest man in the world? Tsutomu Yamaguchi, double A-bomb victim |first=Richard |last=Lloyd Parry |work=[[The Times]] |date=2009-03-25 |accessdate=2014-09-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140921181444/https://blogs.thetimes.co.uk/section/asia-exile/20579/the-luckiest-or-unluckiest-man-in-the-world-tsutomu-yamaguchi-double-a-bomb-victim/ |archivedate=September 21, 2014 }}</ref> At 8:15 am, he was walking towards the docks when the [[B-29 bomber|American bomber]] ''[[Enola Gay]]'' dropped the [[Little Boy]] [[atomic bomb]] near the centre of the city, only 3&nbsp;km away.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/><ref name=\"independent\"/> Yamaguchi recalls seeing the bomber and two small parachutes, before there was \"a great flash in the sky, and I was blown over\".<ref name=\"Times\"/> The explosion ruptured his eardrums, blinded him temporarily and left him with serious burns over the left side of the top half of his body. After recovering, he crawled to a shelter and, having rested, he set out to find his colleagues.<ref name=\"Times\"/> They had also survived and together they spent the night in an [[air-raid shelter]] before returning to Nagasaki the following day.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/><ref name=\"Times\"/> In Nagasaki, he received treatment for his wounds and, despite being heavily bandaged, he reported for work on August 9.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Mr Yamaguchi|url=http://www.vaguedirection.com/mr-yamaguchi/|website=www.vaguedirection.com|publisher=VagueDirection}}</ref>\n\n===Nagasaki bombing===\nAt 11 am on August 9, Yamaguchi was describing the blast in Hiroshima to his supervisor, when the American bomber ''[[Bockscar]]'' dropped the [[Fat Man]] atomic bomb over the city. His workplace again put him 3&nbsp;km from [[ground zero]], but this time he was unhurt by the explosion.<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/how-i-survived-hiroshima-ndash-and-then-nagasaki-1654294.html|title=How I survived Hiroshima \u2013 and then Nagasaki|last=McNeill|first=David|date=26 March 2009|work=[[The Independent]]|publisher=|accessdate=2009-03-26}}</ref> However, he was unable to replace his now ruined bandages and he suffered from a high fever and continuous vomiting for over a week.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/>\n\n==Later life==\nDuring the Allied [[occupation of Japan]], Yamaguchi worked as a translator for the occupation forces. In the early 1950s, he and his wife, who was also a survivor of the Nagasaki atomic bombing, had two daughters. He later returned to work for Mitsubishi designing oil tankers.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> When the Japanese government officially recognized atomic bombing survivors as [[hibakusha]] in 1957, Yamaguchi's identification stated only that he had been present at Nagasaki. He was content with this, satisfied that he was relatively healthy and put the experiences behind him.<ref name=\"independent\"/>\n\nAs he grew older, his opinions about the use of atomic weapons began to change. In his eighties, he wrote a book about his experiences ([http://www.worldcat.org/title/ikasareteiru-inochi/oclc/261349783 ''Ikasareteiru inochi'']), as well as a book of poetry ([http://www.worldcat.org/title/and-the-river-flowed-as-a-raft-of-corpses-the-poetry-of-yamaguchi-tsutomu-survivor-of-both-hiroshima-and-nagasaki/oclc/691426162]) and was invited to take part in a 2006 documentary about 165 double A-bomb survivors (known as nij\u016b hibakusha in Japan) called ''Twice Survived: The Doubly Atomic Bombed of Hiroshima and Nagasaki'', which was screened at the [[United Nations]].<ref name=\"Twice\">{{cite web|url=http://www.columbia.edu/cu/news/06/08/twicesurvived.html|title=Twice Bombed, Twice Survived: Film Explores Untold Stories from Hiroshima & Nagasaki|date=August 2, 2006|publisher=Columbia University |accessdate=2009-03-31}}</ref> At the screening, he pleaded for the abolition of atomic weapons.<ref name=\"independent\"/>\n\nYamaguchi became a vocal proponent of [[nuclear disarmament]].<ref name=\"milhistory\">{{cite journal|title=Japanese Engineer Survived Atomic Strike on Hiroshima ''and'' Nagasaki|journal=Military History Magazine|volume=26|issue=5|page=8|editor=Robbins, M W| publisher=Wieder History Group|date=August\u2013September 2009}}</ref> He told an interviewer \"The reason that I hate the atomic bomb is because of what it does to the dignity of human beings\".<ref name=\"milhistory\"/> Speaking through his daughter during a telephone interview, he said, \"I can't understand why the world cannot understand the agony of the nuclear bombs. How can they keep developing these weapons?\"<ref name=\"independent\"/>.\n\nOn December 22, 2009, Canadian movie director [[James Cameron]] and author [[Charles R. Pellegrino|Charles Pellegrino]] met Yamaguchi while he was in a hospital in Nagasaki and discussed the idea of making a film about nuclear weapons. \"I think it's Cameron's and Pellegrino's destiny to make a film about nuclear weapons\", Yamaguchi said.<ref name=\"monstersandcritics\">{{cite web|url=http://www.monstersandcritics.com/people/news/article_1523351.php/James-Cameron-meets-Japanese-atomic-bomb-survivor-to-discuss-film|title=James Cameron meets Japanese atomic bomb survivor to discuss film|date=January 5, 2010|publisher=Splash News|accessdate=2010-01-06|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108062545/http://www.monstersandcritics.com/people/news/article_1523351.php/James-Cameron-meets-Japanese-atomic-bomb-survivor-to-discuss-film|archivedate=January 8, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Recognition by government===\nAt first, Yamaguchi did not feel the need to draw attention to his double survivor status.<ref name=\"independent\"/> However, in later life he began to consider his survival as destiny, so in January 2009, he applied for double recognition.<ref name=\"independent\"/> This was accepted by the Japanese government in March 2009, making Yamaguchi the only person officially recognised as a survivor of both bombings.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/><ref name=\"independent\"/> Speaking of the recognition, he said, \"My double radiation exposure is now an official government record. It can tell the younger generation the horrifying history of the atomic bombings even after I die\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Japanese man is a double A-bomb survivor|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/29865222|work=NBC News|date=2009-03-25 |accessdate=2010-01-11}}</ref>\n\n===Health===\nYamaguchi lost hearing in his left ear as a result of the Hiroshima explosion. He also went bald temporarily and his daughter recalls that he was constantly swathed in bandages until she reached the age of 12.<ref name=\"independent\"/>{{#tag:ref|Toshiko Yamaguchi was 60 in March 2009 and would have been 12 in 1960 or 1961.<ref name=\"independent\"/>|group=\"Note\"}} Despite this, Yamaguchi went on to lead a healthy life.<ref name=\"independent\" /> Late in his life he began to suffer from radiation-related ailments, including [[cataracts]] and acute [[leukemia]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Justin|last=McCurry|title=Hiroshima and Nagasaki survivor dies aged 93|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/jan/06/hiroshima-nagasaki-survivor-dies|work=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|date=2010-01-06|accessdate=2010-01-08}}</ref>\n\nHis wife also suffered radiation poisoning from [[Nuclear fallout|black rain]] after the Nagasaki explosion and died in 2010 (age 93) of [[kidney cancer|kidney]] and [[liver cancer]]. All three of their children reported suffering from health problems they blamed on their parents' exposures,<ref name=\"independent\"/>{{medrs|date=August 2017}} but studies suggest that in general the children of atomic bomb survivors do not have a higher incidence of disease.<ref>{{Citation|title=Nukes: The Broadcast|url=http://www.radiolab.org/story/nukes-broadcast/|language=en|accessdate=2017-10-08}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\n{{wikinews|Japanese survivor of both Hiroshima & Nagasaki atomic bombings dies, aged 93}}\nIn 2009, Yamaguchi learned that he was dying of [[stomach cancer]].<ref name=\"independent\"/> He died on January 4, 2010, in [[Nagasaki]] at the age of 93.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/><ref>{{Cite news|author=Richard Lloyd Parry|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article6978319.ece|title=Tsutomu Yamaguchi, victim of Japan's two atomic bombs, dies aged 93|newspaper=The Times|date=2010-01-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author=\u963f\u90e8\u5f18\u8ce2|author2=\u5bae\u4e0b\u6b63\u5df1|url=http://mainichi.jp/select/wadai/news/20100106ddm041040050000c.html|script-title=ja:\u5c71\u53e3\u5f4a\u3055\u3093\u6b7b\u53bb\uff1a\u300c8\u67086\u30019\u65e5\u306f\u547d\u65e5\u300d\u3000\u300c\u9752\u304d\u5730\u7403\u300d\u3068\u77ed\u6b4c\u306b\u601d\u3044|work=\u6bce\u65e5jp|quote=[[Mainichi Shimbun]]|date=2010-01-06|language=Japanese|accessdate=2010-01-06}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Japan survivor of both atomic bombs dies, aged 93|work=BBC News|date=2010-01-06|accessdate=2010-01-07|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/8443295.stm}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2010/01/06/world/AP-AS-Japan-Obit-Bomb-Victim.html|title=Double Atomic Bomb Survivor Dies in Japan|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=2010-01-06}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref>\n\n==BBC controversy==\nOn December 17, 2010, the [[BBC]] featured Yamaguchi in its comedy program ''[[QI]]'', referring to him as \"[[QI (H series)#Episode 13 \"Holidays\"|The Unluckiest Man in the World]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|author=BBC|date=2010-12-13|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/comedy/clips/p00cqcrb/qi_the_unluckiest_man_in_the_world/|title=The Unluckiest Man in the World|accessdate=January 21, 2011}}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Both [[Stephen Fry]], the host of ''QI'', and celebrity guests drew laughter from the audience in a segment that included examples of [[black humor]] such as asking if the bomb had \"landed on him and bounced off\".<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC Apologizes for Atomic Bomb Jokes|author=Gavin J. Blair|date=2011-01-24|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bbc-apologizes-atomic-bomb-jokes-74916|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|location=Tokyo|accessdate=2011-01-24}}</ref> A clip from the episode was uploaded by the BBC after the show but was later deleted. A BBC spokesperson told [[Kyodo News]], \"We instructed our crew to delete the file since we have already issued a statement that the content was not appropriate\".<ref>{{cite news|script-title=ja:\u4e8c\u91cd\u88ab\u7206\u8005\u306b\u300c\u4e16\u754c\u4e00\u904b\u304c\u60aa\u3044\u7537\u300d\u767a\u8a00\u3001\u82f1\uff22\uff22\uff23\u304c\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u6620\u50cf\u3084\u3063\u3068\u524a\u9664|date=2011-01-24|url=http://sankei.jp.msn.com/world/news/110125/erp11012507100025-n1.htm|newspaper=[[Sankei Shimbun]]|agency=[[Kyodo News]]|publisher=The Sankei Shimbun & Sankei Digital|accessdate=2011-01-24|language=Japanese|trans-title=BBC Finally Deletes the Video Clip|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110128025653/http://sankei.jp.msn.com/world/news/110125/erp11012507100025-n1.htm|archivedate=2011-01-28}}</ref>\n\nThe episode triggered criticism in Japan. Toshiko Yamasaki, Yamaguchi's daughter, appeared on [[NHK]]'s national evening news and said: \"I cannot forgive the atomic bomb experience being laughed at in Britain, which has nuclear weapons of its own. I think this shows that the horror of atomic bomb is not well enough understood in the world. I feel sad rather than angry\".<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC sorry for jokes about atom bomb survivor|author=Richard Lloyd Parry|date=2011-01-22|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/media/bbc-sorry-for-jokes-about-atom-bomb-survivor/story-e6frg996-1225992837549|newspaper=The Times|publisher=[[The Australian]]|location=London|accessdate= 2011-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Quite Insensitive: BBC quiz's jokes about survivor of both A-bombs outrages Japan|author=Paul Revoir|date=2011-01-22|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1349517/Quite-Insensitive-BBC-quizs-jokes-survivor-A-bombs-outrages-Japan.html|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|publisher=[[Daily Mail and General Trust]]|location=London|accessdate= 2011-02-19}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Japanese Embassy, London]], wrote to the BBC protesting that the programme insulted the deceased victims of the atomic bomb. It was reported that [[Piers Fletcher]], a producer of the programme, responded to complaints with \"we greatly regret it when we cause offence\" and \"it is apparent to me that I underestimated the potential sensitivity of this issue to Japanese viewers\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Japan protests to BBC over treatment of 'double A-bomb survivor'|newspaper=Kyodo News|publisher=Japan Today|location=London|date=January 21, 2011|url=http://japantoday.com/category/national/view/japan-protests-to-bbc-over-treatment-of-double-a-bomb-survivor|accessdate=January 21, 2011}}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nOn January 22, 2011, the BBC and [[Talkback Thames]] jointly issued a statement.<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC offers apology about 'double A-bomb survivor'|url=http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/news/20110122p2g00m0dm014000c.html|agency=Kyodo News|publisher=[[Mainichi Shimbun]]|location=London|date=2011-01-22|accessdate=2011-01-22|quote=QI never sets out to cause offence with any of the people or subjects it covers, however on this occasion, given the sensitivity of the subject matter for Japanese viewers, we understand why they did not feel it appropriate for inclusion|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110123183825/http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/news/20110122p2g00m0dm014000c.html|archivedate=2011-01-23}}</ref> In addition to the joint statement, the BBC delivered a letter from [[Mark Thompson (television executive)|Mark Thompson]], Director-General of the BBC, to the Japanese Embassy.<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC\u3001\u65e5\u672c\u5927\u4f7f\u9928\u306b\u8b1d\u7f6a\u306e\u66f8\u7c21\u3000\u4e8c\u91cd\u88ab\u7206\u8005\u7b11\u3063\u305f\u653e\u9001|author= \u4f0a\u6771\u548c\u8cb4|url= http://www.asahi.com/international/update/0125/TKY201101250107.html|newspaper=[[Asahi Shimbun]]|location=London|date=2011-01-25|accessdate=2011-01-25|language=Japanese|trans-title=BBC Sends Apology Letter to Japanese Embassy for Its Program Laughed at Double A-bomb Survivor|quote= \u5728\u82f1\u65e5\u672c\u5927\u4f7f\u9928\u306f24\u65e5\u3001BBC\u304b\u3089\u9673\u8b1d\u306e\u610f\u3092\u8868\u3059\u66f8\u7c21\u3092\u53d7\u3051\u53d6\u3063\u305f\u3002\u5927\u4f7f\u9928\u306b\u3088\u308b\u3068\u3001\u66f8\u7c21\u306fBBC\u306e\u30c8\u30f3\u30d7\u30bd\u30f3\u4f1a\u9577\u540d\u306721\u65e5\u4ed8\u3002\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u8996\u8074\u8005\u3089\u306e\u6c17\u5206\u3092\u5bb3\u3057\u305f\u3053\u3068\u3092\u9673\u8b1d\u3059\u308b\u5185\u5bb9\u3060\u3063\u305f\u3068\u3044\u3046\u3002}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Effects of nuclear explosions]]\n* [[Effects of nuclear explosions on human health]]\n* [[Jacob Beser]], the only member of the strike crews for both Hiroshima and Nagasaki\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://naosite.lb.nagasaki-u.ac.jp/dspace/handle/10069/25531 Nagasaki University Peace Studies Archives June 2011 YAMASAKI, Toshiko and HARADA, Kosuzu \"Living with a double A-bomb survivor\" {{in lang|en|ja}}]\n* [http://hdl.handle.net/10069/33740 YAMAGUCHI, Tsutomu \"Double A-Bomb Victim: My Life beneath the Atomic Clouds\" 2007]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yamaguchi, Tsutomu}}\n[[Category:Japanese anti\u2013nuclear weapons activists]]\n[[Category:People from Nagasaki Prefecture]]\n[[Category:1916 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:Hibakusha]]\n[[Category:Deaths from stomach cancer]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Japanese atomic bombing survivor}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name       = Tsutomu Yamaguchi\n|native_name= \u5c71\u53e3 \u5f4a\n|native_name_lang=ja\n|image      = Tsutomu-Yamaguchi-Japanes-001.jpg\n|caption    = Tsutomu Yamaguchi in 2009\n|birth_date = {{Birth date|1916|3|16|mf=y}}\n|birth_place= [[Nagasaki]], [[Empire of Japan|Japan]]\n|death_date = {{Death date and age|2010|1|4|1916|3|16|mf=y}}\n|death_place= [[Nagasaki]], [[Japan]]\n|occupation = [[Engineer]]\n|spouse     =\n|children   = 3\n}}\n{{Nihongo|'''Tsutomu Yamaguchi'''|\u5c71\u53e3 \u5f4a|Yamaguchi Tsutomu|}} (March 16, 1916{{spaced ndash}}January 4, 2010) was a survivor of both the [[Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki|Hiroshima and Nagasaki atomic bombings]] during [[World War II]]. Although at least 70 people are known to have been affected by both bombings,<ref>{{cite news|script-title=ja:\u5e83\u5cf6\u30fb\u9577\u5d0e\u3067\uff12\u5ea6\u88ab\u7206\u3001\u7d04\uff11\uff16\uff10\u4eba\u3000\u5e83\u5cf6\u7948\u5ff5\u9928\u304c\u8abf\u67fb|newspaper=[[Asahi Shimbun]]|date=2005-08-01|language= Japanese|trans-title=160 Double A-bomb Survivors Found, [[Hiroshima National Peace Memorial Hall for the Atomic Bomb Victims]] says.|quote= \u5e83\u5cf6\u3001\u9577\u5d0e\u3078\u306e\u539f\u7206\u6295\u4e0b\u5f8c\u3001\u4e21\u5e02\u3067\uff12\u5ea6\u88ab\u7206\u3057\u305f\u53ef\u80fd\u6027\u306e\u3042\u308b\u4eba\u304c\u5c11\u306a\u304f\u3068\u3082\u7d04\uff11\uff16\uff10\u4eba\u306b\u306e\u307c\u308b\u3053\u3068\u304c\u3001\u56fd\u7acb\u5e83\u5cf6\u539f\u7206\u6b7b\u6ca1\u8005\u8ffd\u60bc\u5e73\u548c\u7948\u5ff5\u9928\uff08\u5e83\u5cf6\u5e02\uff09\u306e\u8abf\u67fb\u3067\u660e\u3089\u304b\u306b\u306a\u3063\u305f\u3002}}</ref> he is the only person to have been officially recognized by the [[government of Japan]] as surviving both explosions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Double atomic bomb survivor dies in Japan|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/34722073|agency=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[NBC News]]|location=Tokyo|date=2010-01-06|accessdate=2011-01-25|quote=Tsutomu Yamaguchi, the only person officially recognized as a survivor of both the Hiroshima and Nagasaki atomic bombings at the end of World War II, has died at age 93.}}</ref>\n\nYamaguchi, a resident of [[Nagasaki]], was in [[Hiroshima]] on business for his employer [[Mitsubishi Heavy Industries]] when the city was bombed at 8:15&nbsp;am, on August 6, 1945. He returned to Nagasaki the following day and, despite his wounds, he returned to work on August 9, the day of the second atomic bombing. That morning, whilst being berated by his supervisor as \"crazy\" after describing how one bomb had destroyed the city, the Nagasaki bomb detonated.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9_VsNZl6LGU&t=1m6s Survivor's story (ABC News, Australia, uploaded 2010Jan6)]</ref> In 1957, he was recognized as a [[hibakusha]] (''explosion-affected person'') of the Nagasaki bombing, but it was not until March 24, 2009, that the government of Japan officially recognized his presence in Hiroshima three days earlier. He died of [[stomach cancer]] on January 4, 2010, at the age of 93.\n\n==Early life==\nYamaguchi was born on March 16, 1916. He joined [[Mitsubishi Heavy Industries]] in the 1930s and worked as a draftsman designing oil tankers.<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news|author=|title=Tsutomu Yamaguchi|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/6943088/Tsutomu-Yamaguchi.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=2010-01-06|accessdate=2010-01-07}}</ref>\n\n==Second World War==\nYamaguchi \"never thought Japan should start a war\". He continued his work with Mitsubishi Heavy Industries, but soon Japanese industry began to suffer heavily as resources became scarce and tankers were sunk.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> As the war ground on, he was so despondent over the state of the country that he considered [[Seppuku#In_modern_times|killing his]] [[familicide|family]] with an overdose of [[sleeping pills]] in the event that Japan lost.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/>\n\n===Hiroshima bombing===\nYamaguchi lived and worked in Nagasaki, but in the summer of 1945 he was in Hiroshima for a three-month-long business trip.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> On August 6 he was preparing to leave the city with two colleagues, Akira Iwanaga and Kuniyoshi Sato, and was on his way to the station when he realised he had forgotten his [[Hanko (stamp)|hanko]] (a type of travel stamp common in Japan) and returned to his workplace to get it.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news|first=Justin|last=McCurry|title=A little deaf in one ear \u2013 meet the Japanese man who survived Hiroshima and Nagasaki|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/mar/25/hiroshima-nagasaki-survivor-japan|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=2009-03-25|accessdate=2010-01-11|location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"Times\">{{cite web|url=https://blogs.thetimes.co.uk/section/asia-exile/20579/the-luckiest-or-unluckiest-man-in-the-world-tsutomu-yamaguchi-double-a-bomb-victim/ |title=The luckiest or unluckiest man in the world? Tsutomu Yamaguchi, double A-bomb victim |first=Richard |last=Lloyd Parry |work=[[The Times]] |date=2009-03-25 |accessdate=2014-09-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140921181444/https://blogs.thetimes.co.uk/section/asia-exile/20579/the-luckiest-or-unluckiest-man-in-the-world-tsutomu-yamaguchi-double-a-bomb-victim/ |archivedate=September 21, 2014 }}</ref> At 8:15 am, he was walking towards the docks when the [[B-29 bomber|American bomber]] ''[[Enola Gay]]'' dropped the [[Little Boy]] [[atomic bomb]] near the centre of the city, only 3&nbsp;km away.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/><ref name=\"independent\"/> Yamaguchi recalls seeing the bomber and two small parachutes, before there was \"a great flash in the sky, and I was blown over\".<ref name=\"Times\"/> The explosion ruptured his eardrums, blinded him temporarily and left him with serious burns over the left side of the top half of his body. After recovering, he crawled to a shelter and, having rested, he set out to find his colleagues.<ref name=\"Times\"/> They had also survived and together they spent the night in an [[air-raid shelter]] before returning to Nagasaki the following day.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/><ref name=\"Times\"/> In Nagasaki, he received treatment for his wounds and, despite being heavily bandaged, he reported for work on August 9.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Mr Yamaguchi|url=http://www.vaguedirection.com/mr-yamaguchi/|website=www.vaguedirection.com|publisher=VagueDirection}}</ref>\n\n===Nagasaki bombing===\nAt 11 am on August 9, Yamaguchi was describing the blast in Hiroshima to his supervisor, when the American bomber ''[[Bockscar]]'' dropped the [[Fat Man]] atomic bomb over the city. His workplace again put him 3&nbsp;km from [[ground zero]], but this time he was unhurt by the explosion.<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/how-i-survived-hiroshima-ndash-and-then-nagasaki-1654294.html|title=How I survived Hiroshima \u2013 and then Nagasaki|last=McNeill|first=David|date=26 March 2009|work=[[The Independent]]|publisher=|accessdate=2009-03-26}}</ref> However, he was unable to replace his now ruined bandages and he suffered from a high fever and continuous vomiting for over a week.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/>\n\n==Later life==\nDuring the Allied [[occupation of Japan]], Yamaguchi worked as a translator for the occupation forces. In the early 1950s, he and his wife, who was also a survivor of the Nagasaki atomic bombing, had two daughters. He later returned to work for Mitsubishi designing oil tankers.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> When the Japanese government officially recognized atomic bombing survivors as [[hibakusha]] in 1957, Yamaguchi's identification stated only that he had been present at Nagasaki. He was content with this, satisfied that he was relatively healthy and put the experiences behind him.<ref name=\"independent\"/>\n\nAs he grew older, his opinions about the use of atomic weapons began to change. In his eighties, he wrote a book about his experiences ([http://www.worldcat.org/title/ikasareteiru-inochi/oclc/261349783 ''Ikasareteiru inochi'']), as well as a book of poetry ([http://www.worldcat.org/title/and-the-river-flowed-as-a-raft-of-corpses-the-poetry-of-yamaguchi-tsutomu-survivor-of-both-hiroshima-and-nagasaki/oclc/691426162]) and was invited to take part in a 2006 documentary about 165 double A-bomb survivors (known as nij\u016b hibakusha in Japan) called ''Twice Survived: The Doubly Atomic Bombed of Hiroshima and Nagasaki'', which was screened at the [[United Nations]].<ref name=\"Twice\">{{cite web|url=http://www.columbia.edu/cu/news/06/08/twicesurvived.html|title=Twice Bombed, Twice Survived: Film Explores Untold Stories from Hiroshima & Nagasaki|date=August 2, 2006|publisher=Columbia University |accessdate=2009-03-31}}</ref> At the screening, he pleaded for the abolition of atomic weapons.<ref name=\"independent\"/>\n\nYamaguchi became a vocal proponent of [[nuclear disarmament]].<ref name=\"milhistory\">{{cite journal|title=Japanese Engineer Survived Atomic Strike on Hiroshima ''and'' Nagasaki|journal=Military History Magazine|volume=26|issue=5|page=8|editor=Robbins, M W| publisher=Wieder History Group|date=August\u2013September 2009}}</ref> He told an interviewer \"The reason that I hate the atomic bomb is because of what it does to the dignity of human beings\".<ref name=\"milhistory\"/> Speaking through his daughter during a telephone interview, he said, \"I can't understand why the world cannot understand the agony of the nuclear bombs. How can they keep developing these weapons?\"<ref name=\"independent\"/>.\n\nOn December 22, 2009, Canadian movie director [[James Cameron]] and author [[Charles R. Pellegrino|Charles Pellegrino]] met Yamaguchi while he was in a hospital in Nagasaki and discussed the idea of making a film about nuclear weapons. \"I think it's Cameron's and Pellegrino's destiny to make a film about nuclear weapons\", Yamaguchi said.<ref name=\"monstersandcritics\">{{cite web|url=http://www.monstersandcritics.com/people/news/article_1523351.php/James-Cameron-meets-Japanese-atomic-bomb-survivor-to-discuss-film|title=James Cameron meets Japanese atomic bomb survivor to discuss film|date=January 5, 2010|publisher=Splash News|accessdate=2010-01-06|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108062545/http://www.monstersandcritics.com/people/news/article_1523351.php/James-Cameron-meets-Japanese-atomic-bomb-survivor-to-discuss-film|archivedate=January 8, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Recognition by government===\nAt first, Yamaguchi did not feel the need to draw attention to his double survivor status.<ref name=\"independent\"/> However, in later life he began to consider his survival as destiny, so in January 2009, he applied for double recognition.<ref name=\"independent\"/> This was accepted by the Japanese government in March 2009, making Yamaguchi the only person officially recognised as a survivor of both bombings.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/><ref name=\"independent\"/> Speaking of the recognition, he said, \"My double radiation exposure is now an official government record. It can tell the younger generation the horrifying history of the atomic bombings even after I die\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Japanese man is a double A-bomb survivor|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/29865222|work=NBC News|date=2009-03-25 |accessdate=2010-01-11}}</ref>\n\n===Health===\nYamaguchi lost hearing in his left ear as a result of the Hiroshima explosion. He also went bald temporarily and his daughter recalls that he was constantly swathed in bandages until she reached the age of 12.<ref name=\"independent\"/>{{#tag:ref|Toshiko Yamaguchi was 60 in March 2009 and would have been 12 in 1960 or 1961.<ref name=\"independent\"/>|group=\"Note\"}} Despite this, Yamaguchi went on to lead a healthy life.<ref name=\"independent\" /> Late in his life he began to suffer from radiation-related ailments, including [[cataracts]] and acute [[leukemia]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Justin|last=McCurry|title=Hiroshima and Nagasaki survivor dies aged 93|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/jan/06/hiroshima-nagasaki-survivor-dies|work=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|date=2010-01-06|accessdate=2010-01-08}}</ref>\n\nHis wife also suffered radiation poisoning from [[Nuclear fallout|black rain]] after the Nagasaki explosion and died in 2010 (age 93) of [[kidney cancer|kidney]] and [[liver cancer]]. All three of their children reported suffering from health problems they blamed on their parents' exposures,<ref name=\"independent\"/>{{medrs|date=August 2017}} but studies suggest that in general the children of atomic bomb survivors do not have a higher incidence of disease.<ref>{{Citation|title=Nukes: The Broadcast|url=http://www.radiolab.org/story/nukes-broadcast/|language=en|accessdate=2017-10-08}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\n{{wikinews|Japanese survivor of both Hiroshima & Nagasaki atomic bombings dies, aged 93}}\nIn 2009, Yamaguchi learned that he was dying of [[stomach cancer]].<ref name=\"independent\"/> He died on January 4, 2010, in [[Nagasaki]] at the age of 93.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/><ref>{{Cite news|author=Richard Lloyd Parry|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article6978319.ece|title=Tsutomu Yamaguchi, victim of Japan's two atomic bombs, dies aged 93|newspaper=The Times|date=2010-01-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author=\u963f\u90e8\u5f18\u8ce2|author2=\u5bae\u4e0b\u6b63\u5df1|url=http://mainichi.jp/select/wadai/news/20100106ddm041040050000c.html|script-title=ja:\u5c71\u53e3\u5f4a\u3055\u3093\u6b7b\u53bb\uff1a\u300c8\u67086\u30019\u65e5\u306f\u547d\u65e5\u300d\u3000\u300c\u9752\u304d\u5730\u7403\u300d\u3068\u77ed\u6b4c\u306b\u601d\u3044|work=\u6bce\u65e5jp|quote=[[Mainichi Shimbun]]|date=2010-01-06|language=Japanese|accessdate=2010-01-06}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Japan survivor of both atomic bombs dies, aged 93|work=BBC News|date=2010-01-06|accessdate=2010-01-07|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/8443295.stm}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2010/01/06/world/AP-AS-Japan-Obit-Bomb-Victim.html|title=Double Atomic Bomb Survivor Dies in Japan|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=2010-01-06}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref>\n\n==BBC controversy==\nOn December 17, 2010, the [[BBC]] featured Yamaguchi in its comedy program ''[[QI]]'', referring to him as \"[[QI (H series)#Episode 13 \"Holidays\"|The Unluckiest Man in the World]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|author=BBC|date=2010-12-13|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/comedy/clips/p00cqcrb/qi_the_unluckiest_man_in_the_world/|title=The Unluckiest Man in the World|accessdate=January 21, 2011}}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Both [[Stephen Fry]], the host of ''QI'', and celebrity guests drew laughter from the audience in a segment that included examples of [[black humor]] such as asking if the bomb had \"landed on him and bounced off\".<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC Apologizes for Atomic Bomb Jokes|author=Gavin J. Blair|date=2011-01-24|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bbc-apologizes-atomic-bomb-jokes-74916|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|location=Tokyo|accessdate=2011-01-24}}</ref> A clip from the episode was uploaded by the BBC after the show but was later deleted. A BBC spokesperson told [[Kyodo News]], \"We instructed our crew to delete the file since we have already issued a statement that the content was not appropriate\".<ref>{{cite news|script-title=ja:\u4e8c\u91cd\u88ab\u7206\u8005\u306b\u300c\u4e16\u754c\u4e00\u904b\u304c\u60aa\u3044\u7537\u300d\u767a\u8a00\u3001\u82f1\uff22\uff22\uff23\u304c\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u6620\u50cf\u3084\u3063\u3068\u524a\u9664|date=2011-01-24|url=http://sankei.jp.msn.com/world/news/110125/erp11012507100025-n1.htm|newspaper=[[Sankei Shimbun]]|agency=[[Kyodo News]]|publisher=The Sankei Shimbun & Sankei Digital|accessdate=2011-01-24|language=Japanese|trans-title=BBC Finally Deletes the Video Clip|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110128025653/http://sankei.jp.msn.com/world/news/110125/erp11012507100025-n1.htm|archivedate=2011-01-28}}</ref>\n\nThe episode triggered criticism in Japan. Toshiko Yamasaki, Yamaguchi's daughter, appeared on [[NHK]]'s national evening news and said: \"I cannot forgive the atomic bomb experience being laughed at in Britain, which has nuclear weapons of its own. I think this shows that the horror of atomic bomb is not well enough understood in the world. I feel sad rather than angry\".<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC sorry for jokes about atom bomb survivor|author=Richard Lloyd Parry|date=2011-01-22|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/media/bbc-sorry-for-jokes-about-atom-bomb-survivor/story-e6frg996-1225992837549|newspaper=The Times|publisher=[[The Australian]]|location=London|accessdate= 2011-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Quite Insensitive: BBC quiz's jokes about survivor of both A-bombs outrages Japan|author=Paul Revoir|date=2011-01-22|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1349517/Quite-Insensitive-BBC-quizs-jokes-survivor-A-bombs-outrages-Japan.html|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|publisher=[[Daily Mail and General Trust]]|location=London|accessdate= 2011-02-19}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Japanese Embassy, London]], wrote to the BBC protesting that the programme insulted the deceased victims of the atomic bomb. It was reported that [[Piers Fletcher]], a producer of the programme, responded to complaints with \"we greatly regret it when we cause offence\" and \"it is apparent to me that I underestimated the potential sensitivity of this issue to Japanese viewers\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Japan protests to BBC over treatment of 'double A-bomb survivor'|newspaper=Kyodo News|publisher=Japan Today|location=London|date=January 21, 2011|url=http://japantoday.com/category/national/view/japan-protests-to-bbc-over-treatment-of-double-a-bomb-survivor|accessdate=January 21, 2011}}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nOn January 22, 2011, the BBC and [[Talkback Thames]] jointly issued a statement.<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC offers apology about 'double A-bomb survivor'|url=http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/news/20110122p2g00m0dm014000c.html|agency=Kyodo News|publisher=[[Mainichi Shimbun]]|location=London|date=2011-01-22|accessdate=2011-01-22|quote=QI never sets out to cause offence with any of the people or subjects it covers, however on this occasion, given the sensitivity of the subject matter for Japanese viewers, we understand why they did not feel it appropriate for inclusion|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110123183825/http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/news/20110122p2g00m0dm014000c.html|archivedate=2011-01-23}}</ref> In addition to the joint statement, the BBC delivered a letter from [[Mark Thompson (television executive)|Mark Thompson]], Director-General of the BBC, to the Japanese Embassy.<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC\u3001\u65e5\u672c\u5927\u4f7f\u9928\u306b\u8b1d\u7f6a\u306e\u66f8\u7c21\u3000\u4e8c\u91cd\u88ab\u7206\u8005\u7b11\u3063\u305f\u653e\u9001|author= \u4f0a\u6771\u548c\u8cb4|url= http://www.asahi.com/international/update/0125/TKY201101250107.html|newspaper=[[Asahi Shimbun]]|location=London|date=2011-01-25|accessdate=2011-01-25|language=Japanese|trans-title=BBC Sends Apology Letter to Japanese Embassy for Its Program Laughed at Double A-bomb Survivor|quote= \u5728\u82f1\u65e5\u672c\u5927\u4f7f\u9928\u306f24\u65e5\u3001BBC\u304b\u3089\u9673\u8b1d\u306e\u610f\u3092\u8868\u3059\u66f8\u7c21\u3092\u53d7\u3051\u53d6\u3063\u305f\u3002\u5927\u4f7f\u9928\u306b\u3088\u308b\u3068\u3001\u66f8\u7c21\u306fBBC\u306e\u30c8\u30f3\u30d7\u30bd\u30f3\u4f1a\u9577\u540d\u306721\u65e5\u4ed8\u3002\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u8996\u8074\u8005\u3089\u306e\u6c17\u5206\u3092\u5bb3\u3057\u305f\u3053\u3068\u3092\u9673\u8b1d\u3059\u308b\u5185\u5bb9\u3060\u3063\u305f\u3068\u3044\u3046\u3002}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Effects of nuclear explosions]]\n* [[Effects of nuclear explosions on human health]]\n* [[Jacob Beser]], the only member of the strike crews for both Hiroshima and Nagasaki\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://naosite.lb.nagasaki-u.ac.jp/dspace/handle/10069/25531 Nagasaki University Peace Studies Archives June 2011 YAMASAKI, Toshiko and HARADA, Kosuzu \"Living with a double A-bomb survivor\" {{in lang|en|ja}}]\n* [http://hdl.handle.net/10069/33740 YAMAGUCHI, Tsutomu \"Double A-Bomb Victim: My Life beneath the Atomic Clouds\" 2007]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yamaguchi, Tsutomu}}\n[[Category:Japanese anti\u2013nuclear weapons activists]]\n[[Category:People from Nagasaki Prefecture]]\n[[Category:1916 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:Hibakusha]]\n[[Category:Deaths from stomach cancer]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Japan]]\n", "name_user": "212.56.109.46", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(dhdw)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tsutomu_Yamaguchi"}
